<subSubSection id="071062A1539178B19A94B335EBAC48F0" lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="12" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="description">
<paragraph id="34A88B972499A8BF9FEC119FF9EC600D" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C4FD38E0FE1A56B9248BB2B2793C008D" lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="12" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
Annuals or perennials. Culms 3 cm long (when prostrate) to 170 cm tall, 1-8 mm wide at base, round or sometimes flattened, ascending to erect (sometimes completely prostrate at higher altitudes) or geniculate and rooting at lower nodes (facultatively stoloniferous), branched or unbranched; nodes glabrous; internodes (0.5-)3-26 cm long, soft or sometimes slightly lignified, hollow. Leaf sheaths longer or shorter than the internodes, round or flattened, glabrous on sides and margins; ligules (1.5-)5-12(-15) mm long, hyaline to membranous, apically attenuate but often becoming lacerated due to mechanical damage; blades (3-)5-50 
<normalizedToken id="DB1820C490F4458EE5E73B1849D41048" originalValue="Ã">x</normalizedToken>
0.2-0.6 cm, flat but becoming inrolled when dry, glabrous to somewhat scabrous above and below. Panicles (1.5-)15-105 
<normalizedToken id="396F308AF21CE6B034F1B8E142D17711" originalValue="Ã">x</normalizedToken>
2-30 cm, partially inserted below (subspp. 
<taxonomicName id="388B2230A05B4808E92BD691DAB55AF5" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Diplachne" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Diplachne fusca subsp. muelleri" order="Poales" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="fusca" subSpecies="muelleri">
<emphasis id="75923B49DDCC1BFB0DB1A5EFF9CCAACB" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Diplachne fusca muelleri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="37ACB388BD23AA79C935644F0A87F7C1" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Diplachne" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Diplachne fusca subsp. fascicularis" order="Poales" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="fusca" subSpecies="fascicularis">
<emphasis id="C25BC26533221A423E4BEF87971DF133" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Diplachne fusca fascicularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or occasionally subsp. 
<taxonomicName id="83A8F8AE4A9641045CE5410D8323EFA1" authority="fusca" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Diplachne" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Diplachne fusca subsp. fusca" order="Poales" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="fusca" subSpecies="fusca">Diplachne fusca fusca</taxonomicName>
) to completely exserted at maturity; with (3-)5-35 branches; the branches (1.5-)3-20 cm long, alternate along the rachis, sometimes reflexed or steeply erect but mostly somewhat ascending, stiff, minutely scabrous, axils glabrous. Spikelets 5-12(-14) mm long, shortly pedicillate, sometimes distant near base of branches but overlapping near branch tips; florets (4-)6-12(-20); callus glabrous or hairy; lower glumes 1.0-3.5 (-4.9) mm long, membranous, narrowly ovate to ovate, usually scabrous on the midnerve, apex broadly acute to acute, awnless or infrequently shortly awned; upper glumes 1.8-5.5 mm long, elliptic to usually ovate or widely ovate (or sometimes obovate), scabrous on midnerve, apex obtuse (rarely) or acute at apex, rarely short-awned; lemmas 2.3-6.0 mm long, nar 
<pageBreakToken id="F216BF8840267815E7F3922BB9590459" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" start="start">rowly</pageBreakToken>
ovate, ovate, or elliptic, the lateral nerves distinct and sometimes slightly excurrent, more or less sericeous on lateral nerves and the midnerve (hair tips rounded), apex truncate, obtuse, to acute or acuminate and sometimes bifid, awnless, mucronate, or awned to 3.5 mm; palea subequal or slightly exceeding lemma, more or less sericeous on nerves; apex acute or obtuse. Stamens 1, 2 or mostly 3; anthers 0.2-2.7 mm. Caryopses 1.0-2.4 
<normalizedToken id="432D89FB62B7E4BED48D8A94BFABC98F" originalValue="Ã">x</normalizedToken>
0.7-1.2 mm, elliptic, ovate, or obovate in hilar profile, transversely elliptic to depressed obovate in transverse section, hilar groove lacking, smooth or sometimes slightly rugose, brown; pericarp weakly adnate to the endopserm.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="CAB8CEED7CBE808E71CD2CA2E940C816" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="stem anatomy">
<paragraph id="A2FFD238F172ECA1D6A17AEA7BC9D99D" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Stem anatomy.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C0779683E92C108A48BD90D6FE5390C3" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
Stems are hollow in 
<taxonomicName id="993EBA8FEE408FEF0D012F9322624F96" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Diplachne" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Diplachne fusca" order="Poales" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="fusca">
<emphasis id="DF33DBA33B1FF1F24C81AB76FF94EBA7" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Diplachne fusca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="4D8F9794F609024C5B333A69F07D6227" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1086/334434" author="Canfield, RH" journalOrPublisher="Botanical gazette (London)" pageId="88" pageNumber="89" pagination="636 - 648" refId="B12" refString="Canfield, RH, 1934. Stem structure of grasses of the Jornada Experimental Range. Botanical gazette (London) 95: 636 - 648, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1086/334434" title="Stem structure of grasses of the Jornada Experimental Range." url="https://doi.org/10.1086/334434" volume="95" year="1934">Canfield 1934</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="70FDF1535C086F0E6DD5C055C6267C08" author="Ebinger, JE" journalOrPublisher="Bothalia" pageId="88" pageNumber="89" refId="B22" refString="Ebinger, JE, Carlen, JL, 1975. Culm morphology and grass systematics. Trans. Illinois State Acad. Sci.68: 87-101." title="Culm morphology and grass systematics. Trans. Illinois State Acad. Sci. 68: 87 - 101." year="1975">Ebinger and Carlen 1975</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="DB3E6BE9DF491B6EE13F9C1FB5F70767" DOI="https://doi.org/10.2307/2442093" author="Brown, WV" journalOrPublisher="American Journal of Botany" pageId="88" pageNumber="89" pagination="395 - 402" refId="B10" refString="Brown, WV, 1975. Variations in anatomy, associations, and origins of Kranz tissue. American Journal of Botany 62: 395 - 402, DOI: https://doi.org/10.2307/2442093" title="Variations in anatomy, associations, and origins of Kranz tissue." url="https://doi.org/10.2307/2442093" volume="62" year="1975">Brown 1975</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="E252DE320E871CE2B0ECE51840C5A32F" author="Auquier, P" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the Societe royale de botanique de Belgique" pageId="87" pageNumber="88" pagination="95 - 140" refId="B5" refString="Auquier, P, Sommers, Y, 1967. Recherches histotaxonomiques sur le chaume des Poaceae. Bulletin of the Societe royale de botanique de Belgique 100: 95 - 140" title="Recherches histotaxonomiques sur le chaume des Poaceae." volume="100" year="1967">Auquier and Sommers 1967</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="4CC55AC55BAF9216B2FD3E95702432CB" author="Valls, JFM" journalOrPublisher="Taxon" pageId="94" pageNumber="95" refId="B118" refString="Valls, JFM, 1978. A biosystematic study of Leptochloa with special emphasis on Leptochloa dubia (Gramineae: Chloridoideae). PhD Dissertation, Texas A&amp;M University, College Station." title="A biosystematic study of Leptochloa with special emphasis on Leptochloa dubia (Gramineae: Chloridoideae). PhD Dissertation, Texas A &amp; M University, College Station." year="1978">Valls 1978</bibRefCitation>
). When branching occurs in 
<taxonomicName id="78425F4BC8962168592C1BF43E260F9A" class="Magnoliopsida" genus="D." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="D. fusca" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="fusca">
<emphasis id="052B98F543E52EF020F7D468E8FC10A8" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">D. fusca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it tends to be concentrated in the upper nodes (
<bibRefCitation id="A8CFC98A48523633EA160CAAA94B7C68" author="Valls, JFM" journalOrPublisher="Taxon" pageId="94" pageNumber="95" refId="B118" refString="Valls, JFM, 1978. A biosystematic study of Leptochloa with special emphasis on Leptochloa dubia (Gramineae: Chloridoideae). PhD Dissertation, Texas A&amp;M University, College Station." title="A biosystematic study of Leptochloa with special emphasis on Leptochloa dubia (Gramineae: Chloridoideae). PhD Dissertation, Texas A &amp; M University, College Station." year="1978">Valls 1978</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation id="04146501F23F0AF6C3E90ECCA8FFF2ED" author="Valls, JFM" journalOrPublisher="Taxon" pageId="94" pageNumber="95" refId="B118" refString="Valls, JFM, 1978. A biosystematic study of Leptochloa with special emphasis on Leptochloa dubia (Gramineae: Chloridoideae). PhD Dissertation, Texas A&amp;M University, College Station." title="A biosystematic study of Leptochloa with special emphasis on Leptochloa dubia (Gramineae: Chloridoideae). PhD Dissertation, Texas A &amp; M University, College Station." year="1978">Valls (1978</bibRefCitation>
: 33) observed that branching in 
<taxonomicName id="A6140608600A7D6CDE2E1C8D9DDAC699" class="Magnoliopsida" genus="D." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="D. f. subsp. uninervia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="f." subSpecies="uninervia">D. f. subsp. uninervia</taxonomicName>
tends to occur after the terminal inflorescence is fully developed, suggesting that branching is facultative and dependent on favourable growing conditions, presumably adequate soil moisture.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="97AC0FED97D39357F56BE21BD09BAF3B" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="phenology">
<paragraph id="3846C8CB44AA90F94D6E652DC707FD08" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Phenology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="00A56F53AEDCD3F7C7732112E30C6825" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Flowering throughout the year in tropical latitudes; usually commencing early to mid-summer in temperate areas.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2BC985D16DB951149FB9D6A186A60157" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="distribtution">
<paragraph id="BD5ABD612A93A25E17266F16CF15127E" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Distribtution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C2B3EBB38334AEAC31A47417F07B7FF1" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis id="FFB4FCD8B38FB5A2604D50FA89A11E56" bold="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Native</emphasis>
: Widespread and common to abundant in warm-temperate and tropical areas, between approximately 49Â°N and 40Â°S in the New World and 40Â°N and 42Â°S in Old World; mostly below 2000 m. 
<emphasis id="5786F25BDF2BBB7EF8C2F92C8E9513EA" bold="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Non-native</emphasis>
: See under subspecies.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="55C02027A10AA148733262F1DAFD8178" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="vernacular names">
<paragraph id="98AD9F13DF0E6F5148F440DCF73F3C80" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Vernacular names.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="81955C17BC1F7908F5B487AD1DE55932" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Malabar sprangletop; Chinese: shuang fu cao (åç¨è) (and see others under subspecies).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="7C46426BEA980A890D8B998118DFA052" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="comments">
<paragraph id="6348BE2E8EAD417992A26277207AD230" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="02743C4F56E78C14B5194E40803FC527" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
Localised populations of the 
<taxonomicName id="6F383B5B76B3B7A90913AAF0FA358947" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Diplachne" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Diplachne fusca" order="Poales" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="fusca">
<emphasis id="7DDD5BC36EDB0A7DF057C13768140374" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Diplachne fusca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
complex can be somewhat distinct morphologically from conspecifics occurring elsewhere, which is reflected in the many names that have been created to reflect such variation. However, all characters intergrade when considered globally (
<bibRefCitation id="7B43F52DE3BD81DBB3C18B35032BEDA3" author="Snow, N" journalOrPublisher="Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden" pageId="92" pageNumber="93" refId="B94" refString="Snow, N, 1997a. Phylogeny and systematics of Leptochloa P. Beauv. sensu lato (Poaceae, Chloridoideae, Eragrostideae). Ph.D. dissertation, Washington University in St. Louis: Missouri." title="Phylogeny and systematics of Leptochloa P. Beauv. sensu lato (Poaceae, Chloridoideae, Eragrostideae). Ph. D. dissertation, Washington University in St. Louis: Missouri." year="1997 a">Snow 1997a</bibRefCitation>
), suggesting that the localised morphological variants do not merit recognition at the specific level. Field observations, herbarium work and multivariate statistical studies (Snow unpubl.) based on eleven population samples (n=20) from North America, Africa and Australia, which included over 80 morphometric traits, supported the recognition of four subspecies, which generally can be differentiated with little difficulty. These include: 
<taxonomicName id="87604F0074E533772AAB675E2B1DEE4D" authority="subsp. fusca" class="Magnoliopsida" genus="D." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="D. fusca subsp. fusca" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="fusca" subSpecies="fusca">D. fusca subsp. fusca</taxonomicName>
, a polymorphic Paleotropical taxon adventive in a few areas in the New World (
<bibRefCitation id="C275BB2D93E23B1067E39D463B7CE8FA" author="Nicora, EG" journalOrPublisher="Darwiniana" pageId="90" pageNumber="91" pagination="233 - 256" refId="B63" refString="Nicora, EG, 1995. Los generos Diplachne y Leptochloa (Gramineae, Eragrosteae) de la Argentina y paises limitrofes. Darwiniana 33: 233 - 256" title="Los generos Diplachne y Leptochloa (Gramineae, Eragrosteae) de la Argentina y paises limitrofes." volume="33" year="1995">Nicora 1995</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="0701B1DC6E0E72A4ED7BEE7E4A1ED3B1" author="Snow, N" editor="Zuloaga, FO" journalOrPublisher="3, Tomo 2. Graficamente Ediciones, Cordoba" pageId="92" pageNumber="93" pagination="131 - 138" refId="B99" refString="Snow, N, 2012. Leptochloa P. Beauv. In: Zuloaga, FO, Rugolo, ZE, Anton, AM, Eds., Flora Argentina, Vol. 3, Tomo 2. Graficamente Ediciones, Cordoba: 131 - 138" title="Leptochloa P. Beauv." volumeTitle="Flora Argentina, Vol." year="2012">Snow 2012</bibRefCitation>
); 
<taxonomicName id="DC0A165E5261D67A9C31755C3097D1B7" class="Magnoliopsida" genus="D." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="D. f. subsp. muelleri" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="f." subSpecies="muelleri">D. f. subsp. muelleri</taxonomicName>
, known from much of the interior portions of Australia, particularly the Northern Territory; 
<taxonomicName id="F44F4BB1377A317CEC7F4F2BC48054A4" class="Magnoliopsida" genus="D." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="D. f. subsp. uninervia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="f." subSpecies="uninervia">
<emphasis id="100F2CD1CAE7B2AAD8F93CB7DE486C11" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">D. f. subsp. uninervia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, native to the Neotropics but adventive elsewhere (e.g. 
<bibRefCitation id="16C7A1C967D224B5A1D2C7AAE5B9839B" author="Snow, N" journalOrPublisher="Austrobaileya" pageId="93" pageNumber="94" pagination="299 - 305" refId="B102" refString="Snow, N, Simon, BK, 1999. Taxonomic status and Australian distribution of of the weedy neotropical grass Leptochloa fusca subsp. uninervia, with an updated key to Australian Leptochloa (Poaceae, Chloridoideae). Austrobaileya 5: 299 - 305" title="Taxonomic status and Australian distribution of of the weedy neotropical grass Leptochloa fusca subsp. uninervia, with an updated key to Australian Leptochloa (Poaceae, Chloridoideae)." volume="5" year="1999">Snow and Simon 1999</bibRefCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName id="3A03DCAA449D9532B0CCE5FB6405CFA4" class="Magnoliopsida" genus="D." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="D. f. subsp. fascicularis" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="f." subSpecies="fascicularis">
<emphasis id="FB297476DFE19D2C37A3F9A073753466" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">D. f. subsp. fascicularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, native to the temperate and tropical regions of the New World.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0C3A422FA7FB026C01FFECFD1B0D08BA" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
Differentiating between subspecies can be particularly difficult in parts of California and Argentina, where 
<taxonomicName id="7E4B1086CD732EE1B1913F95C05AD6A9" class="Magnoliopsida" genus="D." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="D. f. subsp. fusca" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="f." subSpecies="fusca">
<emphasis id="6D412189F7B0B30E8059CA6B2F6FC139" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">D. f. subsp. fusca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is adventive and sympatric with 
<taxonomicName id="EE5BBB6A78F9CEC954D9D3052D229D54" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Diplachne" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Diplachne fusca subsp. fascicularis" order="Poales" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="fusca" subSpecies="fascicularis">Diplachne fusca subspecies fascicularis</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="C21CA436C3C3EE44655E4F33286B824E" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Diplachne" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Diplachne uninervia" order="Poales" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="uninervia">
<emphasis id="588FFD6F30106520AFB4AA5C685A6A4C" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Diplachne uninervia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and in the Middle East and Australia (Western Australia, Queensland), where 
<taxonomicName id="C3D331CFB9FE1318836EBB977B67225E" class="Magnoliopsida" genus="D." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="D. f. subsp. uninervia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="f." subSpecies="uninervia">D. f. subsp. uninervia</taxonomicName>
has become established (
<bibRefCitation id="5B051853F2BC8D5F3B8535560FDC0D7F" author="Snow, N" journalOrPublisher="Austrobaileya" pageId="93" pageNumber="94" pagination="299 - 305" refId="B102" refString="Snow, N, Simon, BK, 1999. Taxonomic status and Australian distribution of of the weedy neotropical grass Leptochloa fusca subsp. uninervia, with an updated key to Australian Leptochloa (Poaceae, Chloridoideae). Austrobaileya 5: 299 - 305" title="Taxonomic status and Australian distribution of of the weedy neotropical grass Leptochloa fusca subsp. uninervia, with an updated key to Australian Leptochloa (Poaceae, Chloridoideae)." volume="5" year="1999">Snow and Simon 1999</bibRefCitation>
). It seems unlikely that 
<taxonomicName id="EF5C94DCEF3069CE514231D4353445E0" class="Magnoliopsida" genus="D." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="D. f. subsp. fusca" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="f." subSpecies="fusca">D. f. subsp. fusca</taxonomicName>
has persisted in California.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="841E0AB7D8CE8EB3BC14B481F063F834" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
Specimens collected around wool combing mills in South Carolina in the United States by Ahles and associates in the 1950s and 1960s appear to be 
<taxonomicName id="0907A3BB753EC0CBE6644B6FAED9DDC3" authority="subsp. fusca" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="L." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="L. fusca subsp. fusca" order="Poales" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="subSpecies" species="fusca" subSpecies="fusca">L. fusca subsp. fusca</taxonomicName>
or occasionally subsp. 
<taxonomicName id="AED65E263BF717DC1A8F6D209A0E34F7" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Diplachne" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Diplachne fusca subsp. muelleri" order="Poales" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="fusca" subSpecies="muelleri">Diplachne fusca muelleri</taxonomicName>
, which likely arrived from wool exported by Australia to the Carolinas for the textile factories then common.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2A318CC0049ACB1FC67BEBFDFEE541A0" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" type="key">
<paragraph id="F69E4038E7394B241607564FFD2223C3" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<pageBreakToken id="ECC27FB49D4C6793144D03338EDC26EE" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" start="start">Key</pageBreakToken>
to subspecies of 
<taxonomicName id="EE3434C38A0D28CF2C436F7FEF308109" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Diplachne" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Diplachne fusca" order="Poales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="fusca">
<emphasis id="ED5EA7BD0792609B39573B8CCEA8EDB3" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Diplachne fusca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0FC20F469708741DE7AA2F9665353DE9" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<table id="F0EC12388C267C8BC0A3990BA328C963" inLine="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<tr id="F3B8FEA604ABCC0CD95FDB7A73A36ED9" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<td id="6C9014ADEE9112BB8F47B22BA034FF9E" colspan="1" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" rowspan="1">1</td>
<td id="B7D6677C8CDDDD1A37164F051F8EA0C4" colspan="1" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" rowspan="1">Lowermost panicle branches generally exserted from sheath; uppermost leaf blade length generally shorter than the terminal panicle; leaf sheaths only rarely mottled with anthocyanin pigments; lemmas at maturity smoky white or not, sometimes dark green, but usually lacking a distinct dark spot</td>
<td id="B234B88435E445CF9EA8DF1268F7AC5F" colspan="1" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" rowspan="1">2</td>
</tr>
<tr id="C4F62B2E036034C61E07EADE6563FADE" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<td id="5C22C3EAD6B7D152B3C1E5C4E34DE92C" colspan="1" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" rowspan="1">-</td>
<td id="DDD271493483288034ED27745C0EA0DD" colspan="1" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" rowspan="1">Lowermost branches of panicles generally partially to mostly inserted in upper sheath; uppermost leaf blade length usually exceeding length of panicle; leaf sheaths sometimes mottled with anthocyanin pigments; lemmas often smoky white at maturity and with a dark spot in lower half</td>
<td id="5DD02428987CFCBB4901DB4A3E238F3C" colspan="1" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" rowspan="1">3</td>
</tr>
<tr id="F49E534E095D7D1719C67C5E39FE1516" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<td id="9554C5E6627A53D897F5A8896144FE9C" colspan="1" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" rowspan="1">2</td>
<td id="7A16A7BCFF0F151AF55D6FB6429C3FB6" colspan="1" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" rowspan="1">Lemma apices various, obtuse to acute or acuminate, notched or not; lemmas of various colours; spikelets 6-14 mm; anthers usually 0.5-2.7 mm; mostly Old World, southern South America, introduced into North America</td>
<td id="C309B933318497AE7D95C8348E69C697" colspan="1" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" rowspan="1">
<taxonomicName id="F1359F3B2754F2394AD9B5BC92196A24" authority="subsp. fusca" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Diplachne" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Diplachne fusca subsp. fusca" order="Poales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="fusca" subSpecies="fusca">
<emphasis id="AFFBE44C37302B83469A7BEF3B22F38A" bold="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Diplachne fusca subsp. fusca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</td>
</tr>
<tr id="70A7C54B1D5ADEBE07C492AA5C7BF6CE" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<td id="7F581209A0673564CD321749E87FA326" colspan="1" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" rowspan="1">-</td>
<td id="CF951228DA49E1379172DB2A58DF4483" colspan="1" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" rowspan="1">Lemma apices obtuse to truncate, usually notched and often mucronate; lemmas often dark green or lead coloured; spikelets relatively short, 5-10 mm, anthers usually less than 0.7 mm; rachilla rarely visible during anthesis; mostly New World tropics</td>
<td id="7D6968A92DAAF61ED90521699A58A0F9" colspan="1" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" rowspan="1">
<taxonomicName id="3F2F5610EDEEE3E3997630F04A570024" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Diplachne" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Diplachne fusca subsp. uninervia" order="Poales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="fusca" subSpecies="uninervia">
<emphasis id="538C44FCA079222AB04477A2F7A1DD57" bold="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Diplachne fusca subsp. uninervia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</td>
</tr>
<tr id="BBA9A044FB8CFD5A89550DE0B9D7C72B" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<td id="80975439AE6D6ED69E470180B4D3F7AD" colspan="1" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" rowspan="1">3</td>
<td id="DE7B2CC0F82DE231A66DA98DAB8AAF55" colspan="1" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" rowspan="1">Lemmas flat, relatively broad, to 2.0 mm wide; panicles narrow, mostly less than 5 cm wide; panicle branches generally steeply erect, often flexuous near tips; hairs on lateral nerves of lemma sericeous to velutinous, often densely so and typically becoming divaricate with age; lemma apices mostly broadly acute, awnless or sometimes mucronate; Australian interior</td>
<td id="4AE2E653986B844E61E577F8A711511C" colspan="1" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" rowspan="1">
<taxonomicName id="6F5C8279A8370359823C5F0A3E95E9CF" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Diplachne" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Diplachne fusca subsp. muelleri" order="Poales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="fusca" subSpecies="muelleri">
<emphasis id="CA79E6225F12B93C282BF758865C0B48" bold="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Diplachne fusca subsp. muelleri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</td>
</tr>
<tr id="304976DFC96427DFD96DE79ECF0E3983" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<td id="A0BC65C62DE827811AADF521A183B529" colspan="1" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" rowspan="1">-</td>
<td id="7DBF1BC2D8F9FD30A6431B61EF477D85" colspan="1" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" rowspan="1">Lemmas slightly keeled, relatively narrow, mostly less than 1.5 mm wide; panicles somewhat broad, particularly at base, to 22 cm wide; panicle branches somewhat erect to reflexed, the branches not flexuous near tips; hairs on lateral nerves of sericeous, rarely densely so, typically remaining more or less appressed; lemma apices acute to acuminate, awnless or with awns to 3.5 mm long; mostly New World</td>
<td id="4D3698D9EC309838A0BD7F2A9150A513" colspan="1" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" rowspan="1">
<taxonomicName id="4BFD7F750654341BD42ED2CEB4C8CBC5" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Diplachne" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Diplachne fusca subsp. fascicularis" order="Poales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="fusca" subSpecies="fascicularis">
<emphasis id="D655DD877C0830965CF116660C1CE7A0" bold="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Diplachne fusca subsp. fascicularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</paragraph>
